			<prop.head toc-guid="I2a5ea550630a11eab5989292d3e01631">
				<bop/>
				<bos/>
				<label.name>Chapter</label.name>
				<label.designator>13.</label.designator>
				<headtext>Weight and Sufficiency of Evidence</headtext>
				<eos/>
				<eop/>
			</prop.head>
		</prop.block>
		<message.block>
			<include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright>
		</message.block>
		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id7219dbe682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>13:6.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Number of witnesses</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>One witness is generally enough to establish a fact,[<footnote.reference refid="I7bde9e5074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] but the jury may consider the number of witnesses as going to weight of the evidence.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7bde9e5174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] The preponderance, however, is not necessarily with the greater number.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7bde9e5274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] Thus, most times, the number of witnesses is merely a factor that may affect the weight of the evidence as a whole.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In certain types of cases, more than one witness may be required. <eos/>
						<bos/>Georgia law provides:</paratext>
					<display.quote>
						<para>
							<paratext>
								<begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>
								<?page no="459"?>The testimony of a single witness is generally sufficient to establish a fact. <eos/>
								<bos/>However, in certain cases, including prosecutions for treason, prosecutions for perjury, and felony cases where the only witness is an accomplice, the testimony of a single witness is not sufficient. <eos/>
								<bos/>Nevertheless, corroborating circumstances may dispense with the necessity for the testimony of a second witness, except in prosecutions for treason.<eos/>
								<bos/>
								<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7bde9e5374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
						</para>
					</display.quote>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Also, in criminal cases, an informant who assists and cooperates with a law enforcement agency in gathering evidence against the defendant is not an accomplice, and thus, his testimony alone will be sufficient.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7bdec56074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Even when an accomplice offers the testimony, slight evidence of corroboration connecting the defendant to the crime satisfies the corroboration requirement, and that evidence may be entirely circumstantial.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7bdec56174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] The testimony of one accomplice may also be used to corroborate that of another.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7bdec56274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] However, the corroborating evidence must be independent of the accomplice testimony and must directly connect the defendant with the crime or otherwise support the inference that he is guilty.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7bdec56374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] The trier of fact will decide whether the corroborating evidence is sufficient to convict.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7bdec56474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
		<footnote.block>
			<footnote ID="I7bde9e5074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>1</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-8" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I3972124074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-8</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="1950104310" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3972606274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fields v. Yellow Cab Co. of Atlanta, 80 Ga. App. 569, 56 S.E.2d 845 (1949)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7bde9e5174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>2</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2035539105" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="I3972ae8374d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Pickens, 330 Ga. App. 862, 769, 769 S.E.2d 594, 315 Ed. Law Rep. 1099 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7bde9e5274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>3</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-4" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I3972fca074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-4</cite.query>
							<?page no="459"?>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7bde9e5374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>4</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-8" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I3973bff074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-8</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>See, e.g., <cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="1994039897" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I39740e1274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fain v. State, 211 Ga. App. 399, 439 S.E.2d 64 (1993)</cite.query>, holding that no corroborating testimony was necessary for conviction of drug possession where there was sufficient corroborating physical evidence, i.e., drugs found in his home.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>Slight evidence of corroboration connecting defendant with crime satisfies requirements of <cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-8" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I39745c3074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-8</cite.query> and that evidence may be entirely circumstantial. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="1995122161" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I39745c3374d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Parkerson v. State, 265 Ga. 438, 457 S.E.2d 667 (1995)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7bdec56074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>5</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2008214912" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3974d16274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Moss v. State, 278 Ga. App. 362, 629 S.E.2d 5 (2006)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7bdec56174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>6</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2020779031" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I39756da274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Emory v. State, 301 Ga. App. 771, 774, 688 S.E.2d 682 (2009)</cite.query>: <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“It is not required that the corroboration of the testimony given by an accomplice shall of itself be sufficient to warrant a verdict of guilty, or that the testimony of the accomplice be corroborated in every particular. <eos/>
							<bos/>The amount of corroborative extraneous evidence necessary to connect the accused with the commission of the offense lies peculiarly within the province of the fact finder.”<eos/>
							<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2023472572" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3975bbc274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Daniels v. State, 306 Ga. App. 577, 581, 703 S.E.2d 41 (2010)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2023627772" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3975bbc574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Benbow v. State, 288 Ga. 192, 194–95, 702 S.E.2d 180 (2010)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>“[E]vidence of the defendant&apos;s conduct before and after the crime was committed may give rise to an inference that he participated in the crime.” <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2021221574" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I397609e274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Jones v. State, 302 Ga. App. 147, 149, 690 S.E.2d 460 (2010)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7bdec56274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>7</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2009116931" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I39767f1274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Williams v. State, 280 Ga. 584, 586, 630 S.E.2d 370 (2006)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2024826484" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I39767f1574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Herbert v. State, 288 Ga. 843, 708 S.E.2d 260 (2011)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>“While it is true that a felony conviction cannot be sustained based only on the uncorroborated testimony of one accomplice …, where an additional accomplice provides testimony to corroborate that of the first accomplice, the evidence can suffice to sustain the conviction.” <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2023389327" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I39771b5274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Martinez v. State, 306 Ga. App. 512, 520, 702 S.E.2d 747 (2010)</cite.query> (quoting <cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2003911872" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I39771b5574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Gallimore v. State, 264 Ga. App. 629, 630, 591 S.E.2d 485 (2003)</cite.query>).<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7bdec56374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>8</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2003075165" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3977697274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Baines v. State, 276 Ga. 117, 119, 575 S.E.2d 495 (2003)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7bdec56474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>9</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017250" w-serial-number="2017943849" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3977dea274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Matthews v. State, 284 Ga. 819, 820, 672 S.E.2d 633 (2009)</cite.query>
							.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
